(72,	1,	'2023-07-18 23:25:44',	'2023-07-18 23:25:44',	'<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>William Edward Burghardt Du Bois was born on February 23, 1868, in the predominantly white town of Great Barrington, Massachusetts. He was raised by a single mother and proved to be such a promising student that his church raised money for him to attend Fisk University. Du Bois also earned degrees from Harvard and Friedrich Willhelm University in Germany.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><br>Du Bois became a professor of economics, history, and sociology, as well as a renowned author, a civil rights activist, and one of the founders of the NAACP. He was married twice and had two children. His son, Burghardt, tragically died as a toddler after white doctors refused to treat him. His daughter, Yolande, grew up to become a teacher. Du Bois died in Ghana on August 27, 1963, at the age of 95.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->',	'W. E. B. Du Bois',	'',	'publish',	'closed',	'closed',	'',	'w-e-b-du-bois',	'',	'',	'2023-07-18 23:25:44',	'2023-07-18 23:25:44',	'',	0,	'http://the-book-marketplace.local/?post_type=author-profile&#038;p=72',	0,	'author-profile',	'',	0),
